<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-28T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-28T14:00:00-05:00" n="295" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d295">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9037a: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Counselor of Embassy in China</hi>
                                    (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi></persName>)
                                    <hi rend="italic">at Peiping</hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-28T15:00:00-04:00">July 28, 1937—3
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>141. Did a Japanese liaison officer inform Senior Commandant on or
                                about July 27 that the Japanese intended to launch an attack on
                                Chinese forces both within and without Peiping?<note n="1" xml:id="d295fn1">The Embassy’s telegram No. 325, July 29, 2
                                    p.m., replied: “The Senior Commandant at no time received from a
                                    Japanese liaison officer information” to this effect. “The
                                    nearest approach to that information is that contained in
                                    paragraphs 4 and 5 of my 302 of July 27, 1 p.m.”
                                    (793.94/9063)</note></p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>